[1]
Date: 26 Dec 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Sydney Morning Herald [edited]
<http://www.smh.com.au/news/National/Brazil-beef-imports-suspended-over-FMDs/2004/12/24/1103825082099.html?oneclick=true#>

Brazil beef imports suspended over FMD, 24 Dec 2004
-----------------------------------------------
Australia suspended imports of beef from Brazil on Friday [24 Dec 2004]
after the discovery of foot and mouth disease (FMD) in one of the South
American country's states.
Agriculture Minister Warren Truss said a case of foot and mouth had been
detected in Mato Grosso do Sul, a state bordering Paraguay and Bolivia. The
area had been previously clear of the highly contagious disease.
Although Australia has only ever imported one shipment of beef from Brazil
for processing, all import permits have now been cancelled.
"Biosecurity Australia will now conduct a full review of Australia's
arrangements for importing Brazilian beef to ensure Australia's animal
health status is not compromised," he said in a statement. "The review will
include an on-the-ground audit of Brazil's production and certification
systems. Once the situation in Brazil becomes clearer, my department will
send a team of specialists to undertake a thorough investigation of the
Brazilian meat supply chain."
Australia is one of the few nations in the world to be considered free of
FMD. The last case was in the 19th century.
Mr. Truss said Australia had very strict health and quarantine requirements
for beef and that the nation's food supply chain was safe.
